issuesFound.explanation:
The `inlineValidator` uses `srUtils.markInvalid` / `markValid` to associate error messages, but those helpers only add `aria‑describedby`. They never set `aria‑invalid="true"` on the invalid control nor remove it when the field becomes valid. Consequently screen readers are not informed of validation errors, breaching “SWEEP JS‑D”.  
Fix – modify `srUtils` as follows:  
```js
function markInvalid(field, errorEl) {
  if (!isElement(field) || !isElement(errorEl)) return;
  addDescribedBy(field, errorEl);
  setAttr(field, 'aria-invalid', 'true');          // ← add
}
function markValid(field, errorEl) {
  if (!isElement(field) || !isElement(errorEl)) return;
  if (field.hasAttribute('aria-invalid')) field.removeAttribute('aria-invalid'); // ← add
  // existing describedby cleanup …
}
```  

These changes bring the code into compliance with the required WCAG 2.2 accessibility standards and satisfy the JavaScript ARIA sweeps outlined in the brief.

